b'' b'' b'' b'1-4 bits per r/g/b gives horrible machbanding visible in almost any picture.' b'' b'5 bits per r/g/b colors) gives visible machbanding' b'' b'color-gradient picture has _almost_ no machbanding. this color-resolution is' b'' b'see some small machbanding on the smooth color-gradient picture, but all in all,' b'there _are_ situiations where you get visible mach-banding even in' b'a bit card. if' b'you create a very smooth color gradient of dark-green-white-yellow' b'or something and turn' b'up the contrast on the monitor, you will probably see some mach-banding.' b'' b" while i don't mean to damn henrik's attempt to be helpful here," b"he's using a common misconception that should be corrected." b'' b' mach banding will occur for any image. it is not the color' b"quantization you see when you don't have enough bits. it is the" b"human eye's response to transitions or edges between intensities." b'the result is that colors near the transistion look brighter on' b'the brighter side and darker on the darker side.' b'' b'--andre' b'' b"yeah, of course... the term 'mach banding' was not the correct one, it should've" b"been 'color quantization effect'. although a bad color quantization effect could" b'result in some visible mach-bands on a picture that was smooth before it was' b'quantizised.' b'' b'--' b'chalmers university of technology, sweden.' b'"i haven\'t lost my mind it\'s backed up on tape somewhere."' 